def draw_along_P(probas, values): 
    assert len(probas)==len(values)
    assert abs(np.sum(probas)-1) < 0.000001 # on vrifie que c'est bien une loi de probabi
    x=np.random.uniform(0,1)
    i = 0 
    som_prob=0
    while x > som_prob:
        som_prob+=probas[i]
        i+=1
    return values[i-1]

def EM_multi(samples, m, max_iter=1000, epsilon=1e-3):
    log_likelihoods = []
    X=np.array(samples)
    n, d = X.shape  
    alpha = np.ones(m) / m  # initialisation uniforme
    mu = np.random.rand(m, d)  # initialisation alatoire
    sigma = np.array([np.eye(d) for _ in range(m)])   # initialisation identit
    for _ in range(max_iter): 
        responsibilities = np.zeros((n, m))
        for j in range(m):
            responsibilities[:, j] = alpha[j] * multivariate_normal.pdf(X, mean=mu[j], cov=sigma[j])
        responsibilities /= responsibilities.sum(axis=1, keepdims=True) # normalisation 
        n_j = responsibilities.sum(axis=0)  # nombre de points assigns  chaque cluster
        alpha = n_j / n # On en fait une loi de probabilit
        mu = np.dot(responsibilities.T, X) / n_j[:, np.newaxis]
        for j in range(m):
            diff = X - mu[j]
            sigma[j] = np.dot(responsibilities[:, j] * diff.T, diff) / n_j[j]
        log_likelihood = np.sum(np.log(np.sum([alpha[j] * multivariate_normal.pdf(X, mean=mu[j], cov=sigma[j]) 
                                            for j in range(m)], axis=0)))
        log_likelihoods.append(log_likelihood)

    return alpha, mu, sigma, log_likelihoods
        
        
al, mu, sig, log = EM_multi(samples_multi, 3, max_iter=200, epsilon=1e-4)

plt.ylabel("Log-Likelihood")

def compute_bic(loglik,complexite,nombre_de_points ): 
    return loglik + 0.5*np.log(nombre_de_points)*complexite

def complexite_melange_gaussien(k, d): # 1 gaussienne = mu(taille d), sigma (taille d*d), alpha (taille 1), mais le dernier alpha est dtermin par les k-1 prcdents
    return (k-1)+k*d+k*d*(d+1)/2

def sample_along_q(): # tirage selon q
    sample= np.random.normal(0.8, 1.5)
    return sample

def q(x): # densit q 
    return 1/np.sqrt(2*np.pi*1.5**2)*np.exp(-0.5*(x-0.8)**2/1.5**2)

def p(x): # densit p
    if x <0: 
        return 0
    else : 
        return (x ** (1.65-1) * np.exp(-x**2/2))/1.007368  # pour avoir une densit normalise. On a calcul le facteur de normalisation en intgrant numriquement la densit sur R+

def f(x): 
    if x <0: 
        return 0
    else : 
        return 2*np.sin(np.pi*x/1.5)

N=1000
samples=np.array([sample_along_q() for _ in range(N)])
print('on estime l esprance  ', np.mean(np.array([f(sample)*p(sample)/q(sample) for sample in samples])))

Q4

Il s'agit d'un algorithme EM approch, avec :

  • Une tape pour calculer une approximation de l'intgrale, en utilisant pour cela une estimation par chantillonnage d'importance.

  • Une tape pour mettre jour les paramtres.

Soit : $\gamma_{ij} = \frac{\tilde{\omega}_i^{(0)} \mathcal{N}(x_i \mid \mu_j^{(0)}, \Sigma_j^{(0)})}{\sum_{l=1}^{M} \omega_l^{(0)} \mathcal{N}(x_i \mid \mu_l^{(0)}, \Sigma_l^{(0)})}$

Alors :

$\alpha_j^{(1)} = \frac{\sum_{1\le i \le n} \gamma_{ij}}{\sum_{1\le i \le n} \sum_{1\le l \le n} \gamma_{il}} $

$\mu_j^{(1)} = \frac{\sum_{1\le i \le n} \gamma_{ij} X_i^{(0)}}{\sum_{1\le i \le n} \gamma_{ij}}$

$\Sigma_j^{(1)} = \frac{\sum_{1\le i \le n} \gamma_{ij} (X_i^{(0)}-\mu_j^{(1)}) (X_i^{(0)}-\mu_j^{(1)})^T }{\sum_{1\le i \le n}\gamma_{ij}}$

In[99]:
d_v=5
sigma_2_v=1
b_v=0.4
Sigma_v=np.eye(d_v)
mu_v=np.array([0, 0, 0, 0, 0])


def v(x): 
    assert len(mu_v)==len(x)
    x_copy=np.copy(x)
    x_copy[1]=x[1]+b_v*(x[0]**2-sigma_2_v)
    return 1/np.sqrt((2*np.pi)**d_v*np.linalg.det(Sigma_v))*np.exp(-0.5*np.dot(np.dot((x_copy-mu_v), np.linalg.inv(Sigma_v)), (x_copy-mu_v)))

def v_2D(x,y): # dpendance seulement les deux premires composantes, le reste est une constante
    return v(np.array([x, y, 0, 0, 0]))
In[31]:
def gaussian_mixture(x, mus, Sigmas, alphas): # proba d'observer x selon le mlange gaussien
    return np.sum([alphas[i]*multivariate_normal.pdf(x, mean=mus[i], cov=Sigmas[i]) for i in range(len(mus))])
In[66]:
def draw_gm(alphas, mus, Sigmas, n_samples): # drawing along a gaussian mixture
    assert abs(np.sum(alphas)-1) < 0.000001
    samples=[]
    for i in range(n_samples): 
        x=np.random.uniform(0,1)
        i = 0 
        som_prob=0
        while x > som_prob:
            som_prob+=alphas[i]
            i+=1
        samples.append(np.random.multivariate_normal(mus[i-1], Sigmas[i-1]))
    return samples
In[94]:
def adaptive_importance_sampling(n_max, d, m, n_samples): 
    alphas=np.ones(m)/m 
    mus=[np.zeros(d) for _ in range(m)]
    sigmas=[np.eye(d) for _ in range(m)]
    
    hidden_values = [draw_along_P(alphas, range(m)) for _ in range(n_samples)]
    for _ in range(n_max):

        samples=[np.random.multivariate_normal(mus[hidden_values[i]], sigmas[hidden_values[i]]) for i in range(n_samples)]
        # w_i = celle qu'on veut approximer / q_i = celle qu'on connait donc ici le gaussian mixture model
        w_i=np.array([v(samples[i])/gaussian_mixture(samples[i], mus, sigmas, alphas) for i in range(n_samples)])
        w_i=w_i/np.sum(w_i)
        hidden_values = [draw_along_P(alphas, range(m)) for _ in range(n_samples)] # cluster de gaussienne 
        for i in range(m): # iteration selon les formules de Q4
            mus[i]=np.mean(np.array([samples[j] for j in range(n_samples) if hidden_values[j]==i]), axis=0)
            sigmas[i]=np.cov(np.array([samples[j] for j in range(n_samples) if hidden_values[j]==i]).T)
            alphas[i]=np.sum([hidden_values[j]==i for j in range(n_samples)])/n_samples

        
    return alphas, mus, sigmas
alphas, mus, sigmas = adaptive_importance_sampling(50, 5, 3, 500)
